				<p><img src="http://lgimages.s3.amazonaws.com/data/imagemanager/102691/remove_cover1.jpg" width="222" height="145" /></p>
<p><img src="http://lgimages.s3.amazonaws.com/data/imagemanager/102691/remove_cover2.jpg" width="223" height="163" /></p>
<p><span style="border-radius: 2px; text-indent: 20px; width: auto; padding: 0px 4px 0px 0px; text-align: center; font: bold 11px/20px 'Helvetica Neue',Helvetica,sans-serif; color: #ffffff; background: #bd081c url('data:image/svg+xml;base64,') no-repeat scroll 3px 50% / 14px 14px; position: absolute; opacity: 1; z-index: 8675309; display: none; cursor: pointer;">Save</span></p>

						<div id="s-lg-box-15575850" class="s-lib-box s-lib-box-std">
							<h2 class="s-lib-box-title">Directions
                                </h2>
							<div id="s-lg-box-collapse-15575850" >
								<div class="s-lib-box-content">
									
			<div id="s-lg-content-33974423" class="  clearfix">
				<p><span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Step 1<br /></span></strong>Positioning the slide cartridge as shown (Fig. 1), with the numbering at the top, and with the individual slide facing you, rotate the slide until the image is upside down and insert into the numbered slot. <strong>NOTE: Begin with slot #2. DO NOT place a slide in slot #1. </strong>Fill the cartridge with the desired number of slides, up to 50.<strong><br /></strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Step 2</span></strong><br />Turn the scanner on (on its left rear side). The scanner will calibrate for apx. two minutes (the slide arm will move in and out, and the green light will blink. The light will be solid and the arm closed when complete).&nbsp; Place fingers on both sides of the tunnel cover and press and lift to remove (Fig. 2).<br /></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Step 3</span></strong><br />Slide the cartridge into the tunnel from the left with the numbers facing up and nearest the front of the scanner (Fig. 3). Slide it until it touches the slide arm and feels as though it "clicks" into place. Pull out the slide arm (Fig. 4) and gently push the cartridge forward until you can slide the arm into Slot #1 (the empty slot).<br /></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Step 4</strong></span><br />Having inserted your storage device into a USB port of the computer, open the CyberView X5 software from the desktop. In the upper left corner, select "Scan" &gt; "Preference..." Typically, you will be scanning a positive: select this. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;">1) In the "Scan Settings" tab, locate your storage device in the directory by clicking "Browse." </span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;">2) At this point you can also decide how to name your files. For example, you could type "BritishArt215" into the "Base File Name" field and each slide would be automatically named "BritishArt215_001," "BritishArt215_002," etc.<br /></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;">3) <span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;">Select the file type that you prefer, JPEG or TIF; t<span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;">he program defaults to TIFs of 1000ppi (see below).</span><br /></span></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;">When you have completed these steps, click "OK."<br /></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;">&nbsp; <br /></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;"><img src="http://lgimages.s3.amazonaws.com/data/imagemanager/102691/cyberviewx51.png" width="556" height="354" /></span></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">&nbsp;</span></strong></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Step 5</span></strong><br />To the right side of the main CyberView X5 window, you will see a smaller "Active Frame Setting" window (below). This is where you can adjust the resolution (dpi). We suggest choosing "Custom" and setting the resolution to 300; that is typically large enough for print quality, but the image will be actual size<strong> </strong>(apx. 1.5" x 1.5"). The bigger you need your image to be for eventual use, the higher the resolution should be; just remember that scanning and storage time increase propotionately.</p>
<p><img src="http://lgimages.s3.amazonaws.com/data/imagemanager/102691/active_frame_setting_pic.jpg" width="463" height="334" /></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">&nbsp;</span></strong></p>
<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Step 6</span><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><br /></span></strong>You are now ready&nbsp; to scan. Click "Scan" again in the upper left, select "Scan" &gt;"Multi-Scan to file" and set the range from 2-50, or however many slides you have loaded into the cartridge. <strong>Always begin with 2.</strong> Click "OK." Scanning will beg<strong>in</strong> and will continue until the final slide is complete.</p>
